'''Métis French''' ({{lang-fr|français métis}}), along with [[Michif]] and [[Bungi]], is one of the traditional languages of the [[Métis people (Canada)|Métis people]], and the [[French language|French]]-dialect source of Michif.<ref>Bakker. (1997: 85).</ref>

==Michif==

{{further|Michif language}}
They share a common [[phonology]] and [[morphosyntax]] for the [[noun phrase]] but differ as to their sources for the [[verb phrase]] which is [[Ojibwe language|Ojibwe]]-[[Cree language|Cree]] based in Michif, [[Canadian French|French]]-based in Métis French. Like Michif, Métis French is spoken in Manitoba and North Dakota and adjacent provinces or states. As a general rule, Métis individuals speak one or the other, rarely both.

Métis French is a variety of [[Canadian French]].

